{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2feininger_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280605025/1948072901/0035.xml":{"full_text":"J\nWASHINGTON AND VICINITY\n^THURSDAY, JULY 29, 1948\nHt\nProposal to Sell\nAirbaseHighway\nIrks Planners\nCommission Hopes to\nGet Federal Status\nFor Suitland Parkway\nBy Nelson M. Shepard\nFederal planning officials were in\na quandary today over an unex\npected Army Department move to\nsell the $4,000,000 military Suitland\nParkway connecting Bolling Field,\nthe Suitland tMd.) public buildings\narea and Andrews Air Force Base.\nThey feared it may be too late to\nprevent the War Assets Adminis\ntration from disposing of this con\nnecting link with downtown Wash\nington, unless Congress can be per\nsuaded during the special session to\npass pending bills that would trans\nfer it to the National Park Service.\nThat would give it the status of the\nMount Vernon highway.\nThe question that puzzled half a\ndozen interested Federal and Dis\ntrict agencies was: What would any\npurchaser do with a road 7 miles\nlong, believed entirely imsuited for\nhousing or apartment developments\nover most of its 700-foot width?\nSome officials termed the Army pro\nposal as \u201cimpossible,\u201d and others\nwent so far as to call the idea\n\u201csilly.\u201d\nOfficial Notice Awaited.\nThe National Capital Park and\nPlanning Commission, which opened\nits monthly meeting early today,\nexpected to be advised officially\nabout the Suitland Parkway plan at\ntomorrow\u2019s session. Meanwhile, its\nofficials said the road would bring\nonly about one-tenth of its total\ndevelopment cost, estimated at\n\u201cslightly less than $4,000,000,\u201d if a\nbuyer could be found. Its sale would\nundo the work of years of planning,\nit was claimed.\nIt was learned the Army Depart\nment. wishing to rid itself of the\nburden of maintaining the road,\nhad arranged for its transfer to\nWAA before July 2, the deadline\nfor declaring the property surplus\nunder existing law. It has been\npaying the National Park Service\n$17,000 per quarter year for main\ntaining and policing the parkway.\nPressure will be brought to bear,\nIt was said, to get action on the\ntwo bills now pending before the\nSenate and House Public Roads\nCommittees. The Army, as well as\npark and planning officials, are in\naccord on the legislation and offi\ncials said it could pass easily if re\nported from committees.\nInitiated ueiore war.\nThe parkway was initiated before\nWorld War II. It was planned to\nmake downtown Washington readily\naccessible to Government employes\nin Suitland and also to connect\nwith Andrews Air Force Base. Dur\ning the war the Army received a\n\u201cgo ahead\" signal from President\nRoosevelt to build the project to\nconnect the two largest military air\nfields in this area\u2014Bolling and An\ndrews.\nNow the Army doesn\u2019t need the\nparkway, it was said, and when\nCongress adjourned before the po\nlitical conventions without acting\non legislation transferring the road\nto the National Park Service, it felt\ncompelled to take other action be\nfore it wad1 too late.\nSuitland Parkway is a dual high\nway with limited access roads and\nseveral overpasses and underpasses,\nbuilt not only to avoid traffic haz\nards but also to step up the speed\nof military vehicles. The parkway\nhas never been completed. One\ntraffic lane is unpaved.\nTwo sessions were to be held to\nday by the District planners with\nVirginia and Maryland planning\nofficials.\nThe Alrington County Planning\nCommission was to be host at a\nluncheon meeting at the Washing\nton Golf and Country Club for the\npurpose of discussing zoning prob\nlems. At 3 p.m. the Federal group\nwas to meet in the Interior De\npartment Building with the Mary\nland-National Capital Park and\nPlanning Commission.\nLimited to Small Projects.\nThe Maryland officials are in\nterested in the projects that can be\ndeveloped with the meager $150,000\nappropriated by Congress for the\nacquisition of park lands in various\nstream valleys in Montgomery and\nPrince Georges Counties. With Fed\neral officials they had sought\n$1,500,000 for such developments.\nThe District commission has been\nasked to make a definite recom\nmendation with respect to the Cap\nital Transit Co.\u2019s plan to re-route\nits lines on Pennsylvania avenue,\nbetween Seventh and First streets\nN.W. A hearing will be held before\nthe Public Utilities Commission on\nAugust 11.\nA plan for development of the\nWashington Monument Grounds in\ntime for the 1950 sesquicentennial\ncelebration will be considered by\nthe commission. Maj. Gen. U. S.\nGrant III, chairman, made such a\nsuggestion in an address on July 4\nat the centennial exercises for the\nmonument.\nMoten Heads Arlington\nCouncil of Legion Posts\nC. B. Moten has been elected\ncommander of the Arlington Coun\ncil of American Legion Posts to suc\nceed Pete Dolan, new 8th district\nvice commander. Mr. Moten is the\nretired commander of Arlington\nLegion Post 139.\nOther council officers include:\nBurnette Brooks, vice commander;\nElmer J. Blackmer, jr., county ad\njutant and finance officer, and R.\nC. Davis, chaplain.\nStar Movies\nCommunity movies, sponsored by\nThe Star in co-operation with the\nRecreation Department and The\nFilm Center are scheduled for 9\np.m. today. Programs of comedy,\nsports, cartoons and travel shorts\nwill be shown at the following play\ngrounds and recreation centers.\nBuchanan, Thirteenth and streets SI.\nCongress Heights, Savannah street and\nHandle place S.E.\nDupont-Stoddert, C street off Ridge\nroad 8 E\nGeorgetown. Thirty-fourth street and\nVolta place N.W.\nPowell, Sixteenth and Lamont streeta\nMW.\nRaymond. Tenth and Quebec street*\nHayes. Rlfth and K streeta N.I.\n\u2022treets1!? W*ry' T*ent,-**vent& end I\n\u201cw\u201c*\u201c ,treetb(tw**\u201c\nwalltar. Third and X streets \u00bb,W.\nI\ni\nHIGH SCHOOL YOUTH RECEIVES HORTON AWARD\u2014Morton\nGamerman, 17, of 442 O street N.W., Central High School band\ncaptain, receives the annual Horton cash award from Supt. of\nSchools Hobart M. Coming yesterday at Franklin School. Mrs.\nHyman Gamerman watches her son accept the award, provided\nin Gen. William E. Horton\u2019s will. The prize is given for \u201cper\nformance in military duties, scholastic standing and soldierly\nappearance, including military poise and bearing while per\nforming duties.\u201d \u2014Star Staff Photo.\nRequest by A. B.&W.\nFor Fare Rise Taken\nUnder Advisement\nBy the Associated Press\nRICHMOND. Va\u201e July 29.\u2014The\nState Corporation Commission to\nday had under advisement a re\nquest of the Alexandria, Barcroft\nWashington Transit Co. for passen\nger fare increases which a company\nofficial said would mean a net profit\nof about $95,000 annually for the\nfirm.\na six-month trial basis were ap\nproved for the company by the In\nterstate Commerce Commission in\nWashington Tuesday.\nThe company, whose intrastate\nand interstate operations in Arling\nton, Fairfax. Alexandria and the\nDistrict of Columbia are virtually\ninseparable, is asking authority to\nincrease its present 5-cent fares to\na dime, with bus tokens at two for\n15 cents, and boost its 10-cent fares\nto 15 cents, subject to the use of\na 7tz-cent token plus a nickel. The\ncompany said that virtually the en\ntire effect of the increase would be\n2>/i cents.\nVirtually No Opposition.\nRepresentatives of the Citizens\nRapid Transit Co. of Newport News\nwhose properties were sized by the\nState early this month to prevent\na threatened strike, were spectators\nat the A., B. W. hearing. The\nState still is operating the CRT,\nbut the Newport News Transit C&.\u2019s\nrequest for rate boosts is up for a\nhearing before the commission to\nday.\nThere was virtually no opposition\nto the A., B. W. request but Lester\nR. Conley, a member of the Arling\nton County Public Utilities Com\nmission, was on hand to represent\nthe interests of the Arlington\nCounty Board.\nMayor William T. Wilkins of\nAlexandria said he had presented\nthe matter of the A., B. W ap\nplication to the City Council earlier\nthis month. He said the Council\ndiscussed the matter a length and\nreached the conclusion that no ac\ntion should be taken in opposition\nto the petition.\nService Called \u201cMagnificent.\u201d\nMr. Wilkins said the Alexandria\nCouncil well knew \u201cthe magnificent\nservice\u2019\u2019 the A., B. W. had ren\ndered to the city over a period of\nyears. He said it was his belief that\nthe increase was justified.\nThe A.. B. W.\u2019s general man\nager, Beverley C. May, said that the\ncompany's total revenues for the\nfirst quarter of this year amounted\nto $644,311 and the total expenses\nwere $688,728. It was he who esti\nmated the profit of $95,000 if the\nincreases are approved.\nCounty Librarian Reports\nCirculation of 92,425\nStatistics compiled in connection\nwith operation of the Prince\nGeorges County Memorial Library\nindicate the desire county residents\nhave for such services, Mrs. Mary\nB. Kenan, county librarian, reported\ntoday.\nThe county library, which oper\nates a traveling bookmobile and sev\neral permanent libraries throughout\nthe county, had a total circulation\nfrom September 15 of last year until\nlast June 30 of 92,425, Mrs. Kenan\npointed out. This included 583 al\nbums of records, 57 films and 708\npamphlets, pictures and magazines,\nshe said.\nIn the book-lending department,\n9,766 were left at 30 schools and\nwere distributed a total of 33,128\ntimes, Mrs. Kenan said. Children\nin communities of the county took\nhome 33,535 books. A total of 10,686\nbooks was borrowed by Laurel resi\ndents, with Pairmount Heights\nreaders borrowing 9,563 books and\nHyattsville, 7,606. Only 41 out of\nI, 658 requests were unable to be\nfilled by the library.\nThe library system now has a\ntotal of 15,985 volumes, including\nII, 282 purchased with State aid\nmoney and 3,157 given as gifts dur\ning the past year, Mrs. Kenan said.\nPerson Who Set Poodle\nAfire Near Home Sought\nThe Prince Georges County Ani\nmal Rescue League is seeking the\nidentity of the person responsible\nlor setting a Seat Pleasant (Md.i\ndog on fire Monday near its home.\nThe animal, \u201cToodles,\u201d a 4*4-year\nald male poodle dog, is now recover\ning from severe bums at the Stew\nart Animal Hospital, Brentwood,\nvccording to Mrs. Ralph J. Sheffer,\npresident of the league. The dog 1s\nhe pet of Mrs. Laura Brady of\n>09 Seventieth street. Seat Pleasant.\nPull prosecution of the culprit, if\n:aught, was promised by Mrs.\nSheffer.\n3uard Committee to Meet\nA special meeting of the National\nTuard Committee of Hyattsville\nvill be held at 8 o\u2019clock tonight at\nhe Hyattsville Armory.\ni\na\nNational Legislation,\nFilibuster Threats Kill\nD. C. Pay Raise Hopes\nBy Don S. Warren\nThe States\u2019 rights filibuster\nagainst the anti-poll tax bill, to\nstart- in earnest today in the Senate,\nmay sound a death knell to pay\nraises for District Government\nworkers.\nSpokesmen for the District are\ncompelled to stand aside, under the\nspecial session program, until mat\nters of national or emergency im\nportance are settled. This city\u2019s\naffairs, it was regretfully agreed,\nido not fall in that category.\nwithout enactment of measures\nproviding adequate v revenues to\ncover the pay raise costs, Senate\nDistrict Committee leaders say they\ncannot let the pay raise bill pass.\nJohnston's Threat Decides Issue.\nThe threat of Senator Johnston,\nDemocrat, of South Carolina to\nstart another filibuster against the\nHouse-passed sales tax bill, pending\non the Senate Calendar, was a key\nto the decision of Senate Republi\ncans to set the city revenue bill\naside.\nA last-minute appeal may be\nmade to Senator Johnston to with\nhold filibuster tactics and permit\nsome final decision on the city\u2019s\nrevenue crisis. If he were willing\nmerely to state his case for \"the\nlittle people'\u2019 and then let the Sen\nate vote, Senators said, there might\nstill be hope for tax bill action.\nSponsors of the revenue bill,\nhowever, were not optimistic.\nConference Hears Needs.\nThe case of the District\u2019s needs\nwas outlined to the Senate Repub\nlican conference yesterday by\nChairman Buck of the Senate Dis\ntrict Committee and Senator Cain,\nRepublican, of Washington, and\nhead of the District Fiscal Affairs\nSubcommittee. They got an atten\ntion hearing, judging from reliable\nreports, but won only a promise\nthat the District\u2019s affairs would be\nconsidered later\u2014if the Southerners\u2019\nfilibuster was broken, permitting\nother business before adjournment.\nSenator Cain had no complaint\nagainst the conference decision, all\ncircumstances considered.\n\u201cThe conference decided we would\nmeet only long enough to satisfy\nrequirements under proposals made\nby the President, which must be of\nnational significance or emergency\ncharacter.\n\u201cIt is distressingly true that the\naffairs of the District do not fall\nwithin that category.\u2019\u2019\nChances for House action on the\nWashington homerule bill, calling\nfor an elected city government here,\nalso appeared to be exceedingly slim.\nSpeaker Martin told reporters this\nbill may be considered only if the\nHouse decided to take up \u201cgeneral\u201d\nlegislation, outside the issues\nraised in the President\u2019s call for the\nspecial session. House Republican\nprograms were to be drafted at a\nconference this afternoon.\nFort Meade Soldier Dies\nIn Armored Car Crash\nBy the Associated Press\nFORT MEADE, Md., July 29.\u2014A\nyoung soldier was killed here yes\nterday when an armored car in\nwhich he was riding crashed into\na tree.\nThe post public relations office\nidentified him as T/5 Donald Plum\nmer, 19, son of Mrs. Cecelia Plum\nmer of Sidman, Pa. He had been\nin the service 14 months.\nA Reserve Officer Training Corps\nstudent was at the wheel of the\"\nvehicle when it crashed into a hol\nlow pine tree on the driving range\nnear the post hospital area.\nFirst Tick Fever Fatality\nReported in Montgomery\nThe first tick fever death in\nMontgomery County this year has\nbeen reported.\nThe victim was Joseph Galeano.\n52, a plasterer, of the 9*000 block of\nOld Bladensburg road, Silver Spring.\nMr. Galeano died Tuesday in the\nBethesda Naval Medical Center,\nwhere he was admitted July 19.\nCounty health authorities said\nthere have been seven cases of the\ndisease so far this year.\nFairfax Jury Disagrees\nIn Household Larceny\nA Fairfax County Circuit Court\njury yesterday failed to agree in the\nState\u2019s case against Sergt. and Mrs.\nWalter Kosmicki, charged with\ngrand larceny.\nThe Kosmickis. who live at Fran\nconia, were accused of taking about\n$200 worth of household articles\nwhen they moved from a house in\nGum Springs last month. Mrs.\nKosmicki said that while some of\nthe articles were not hers, they may\nhave been moved by mistake.\nSergt. Kosmicki is stationed at\nTort Belvoir.\nCampaign Posts\nFilled by G.O.P.\nIn Maryland\nMiss Adkins Backed\nBy Central Committee\nIrf Vote of Confidence\nCampaign organization plans\nwere perfected yesterday at a meet\ning of the Republican State Central\nCommittee of Maryland, but most\nof the 21/2-hour session in Baltimore\nwas devoted to a defense of Mary\nland\u2019s new national committee\nwoman.\nState Senator Stanford Hoff of\nWestminster, who succeeded the\nveteran Gaftn L. Tait of Chevy\nChase as party chairman last spring,\nannounced appointment of a State\nwide committee which will conduct\nthe campaign for. Gov. Dewey, Gov.\nWarren and the six Repulican\nHouse nominees.\nThis group includes the party\nleader, Jacob Prance, national com\nmitteeman: Miss Bertha Adkins,\nwhose recent choice as national\ncommitteewoman stirred a contro\nversy, and the House candidates.\nCoyle Appointed.\nChairman Hoff also appointed to\nthe committee. William E. Coyle of\nSilver Spring, to serve as chairman\nfor the Young Republicans. Other\nCampaign Committee members are\nRobert O. Bonnell, Baltimore, for\nfinance; former Mayor Theodore R.\nMcKeldin, Baltimore, speakers;\nBlanchard Randall, jr., Baltimore,\nresearch; State Senator Robert B.\nKimble, Allegany County, labor;\nHenry Stockbridge III, Baltimore,\ntreasurer, and Leland Rockwell,\nBaltimore, secretary.\nThe House candidates are Repre\nsentative Miller, 1st District; Rep\nresentative Beall, 6th; A. Earl Ship\nley, 2d; John A. Janetzke, 3d;\nJames W. Miller, 4th, and C.\nMaurice Weidemeyer, 5th.\nThe France organization's floor\nleader at the State convention in\nMay, Paul Fletcher of Allegany, yes\nterday introduced a resolution giv\ning Miss Adkins a vote of confidence\nfrom the Central Committee. It was\npassed unanimously.\nVoting Certificate Presentd.\nThe national committeewoman\u2019s\nselection was criticized by a group\nof women because she has not been\nactive in party affairs and because\nthe organized women were not con\nsulted about their representative.\nMiss Helen E. Brown of Baltimore,\none of the critics, asserted Miss Ad\nkins, who lives in Salisbury, had\nnot voted in Maryland since 1940.\nA certificate signed by a Wicomico\nCounty election official was pre\nsented at the meeting to refute this\ncharge. The certificate said Miss\nAdkins voted in 1946. Her friends\nsaid she had not voted in 1942 and\n1944 because she was out of the\nState.\nFifth Maryland Ferry\nBegins Run Tomorrow\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nANNAPOLIS, July 29.\u2014Resplen\ndent in a fresh coat of white paint,\nMaryland\u2019s fifth ferryboat starts on\nher first run to the Eastern Shore\ntomorrow.\nThe 22-year-old $275,000 Diesel\nelectric ferry, re-christened \u201cThe\nMotorship Eastern Bay,\u2019\u2019 will ply\nacross Chesapeake Bay five days a\nweek.\nThe 11-knot, 145-foot vessel was\nto leave the drydock at Baltimore\nthis afternoon for Sandy Point,\nGeneral Manager B. Prank Sher\nman of the Chesapeake Bay ferry\nsystem said.\nCapt. Joseph P. Marshall of Anne\nArundel County will guide the\nEastern Bay between Sandy Point\nand Matapeake Thursdays, Fridays,\nSaturdays, Sundays and Mondays,\nCapt. Sherman said.\nShe will give the State four\nferryboats during week-end con\ngestion. The ferryboat Harrington,\nwhich has been taken off the\nRomancoke-Claibome run to ease\ntraffic jams at Sandy Point, will\ngo back to her regular run, Mr.\nSherman said.\nThe Eastern Bay, which has a\ncapacity of about 35 vehicles and\n450 passengers, was purchased by\nthe State from a New Jersey utility.\nFinal Action Slated Monday\nIn Arlington Chest Merger\nFinal action of the proposed\nmerger of the Arlington Community\nChest and the Arlington Commun\nity Council will be taken at a joint\nmeeting of the two boards of direc\ntors at 8 p.m. Monday.\nThe merger has been approved in\nseparate actions by Uoth boards un\nder a plan which preserves the\nfunctions of each agency. Accord\ning to B. Alden Lilywhite, head of\na joint merger committee, the plan\n\"combines and integrates the com\nmunity planning services of the\ncouncil and the fund raising and\nfinancial support of welfare pro\ngrams of the Chest.\u2019\u2019\nThe merger was suggested to\n\"promote a program of economy in\nadministration of the two groups\nby bringing them together under\none executive head.\u201d\nProposed as the name of the new\norganization is the Arlington Com\nmunity Chest and Council. Plans\ncall for a board of trustees made\nup of 150 persons from the boards\nof both organizations.\nOfficers will be elected at the\nMonday meeting at 3159 Wilson\nboulevard.\n\u2018MONROE BEACH\u2019 CAPERS, COMMUNITY CENTER STYLE\u2014Residents of the National Capital\nHousing Authority\u2019s Monroe street development enjoy \"beach\u201d activities as Chief Petty Officer\nRaymond Luciana, 610 Lawrence street NJ!., turns the hose on them. The activity, a regular one\nhere on Hot days, is one of many sponsored by the Monroe Community Council for the people\nliving in the project. _ \u2014Star Staff Photo.\nTestimony Expected\nTo End Today in Trial\nOf Mrs. Emmart\nBy the Associated Press\nWOODSTOCK, Va., July 29.\nTestimony in the murder case\nagainst Mrs. Julia Emily Emmart\nin the slaying of her druggist hus\nband last August was expected tc\nbe completed today.\nMrs. Emmart, 45, is charged with\nshooting George Allen Emmart, 45\nin the drugstore he operated in\nStrasburg. He forpierly managed a\nPeoples Drug Store in Alexandria\nThe trial began Tuesday in Shen\nandoah County Circuit Court and\nthe jury was locked up overnight\nin a local hotel.\nYesterday a prosecution witness,\nMrs. Margaruite Snarr, testified\nabout a conversation she said she\nhad with Mrs. Emmart two days\nbefore the August 20 shooting.' The\nconversation occurred in Mrs. Em\nmart\u2019s home, the witness said.\nConservation Quoted.\n\"I am tired of the goings on and\nhumiliation,\u201d Mrs. Snarr quoted Mrs,\nEmmart as saying. She said Mrs.\nEmmart then went into another\nroom and showed Mrs. Snarr a gun,\n\u201cI have a gun and I am going tc\nkill those two Mrs. Snarr\nquoted her as saying then.\nMrs. Snarr said Mrs. Emmart\nreferred to her husband, George\nEmmart and Agnes Craybill, a\ndivorcee, at that time a clerk in Dr.\nEmmart\u2019s drug store. Mrs. Snarr\nsaid the druggist\u2019s wife read off a\nlist of things she wanted to give\nher friends after her death. The\nwitness described Mrs. Emmart as\nappearing an intelligent woman but\nwith a temper not controlled.\nLinden Stickley, Strasburg, a filling\nstation operator and friend of Dr.\nEmmart, testified that Dr. Emmart\nfrequently came to his home and\nthat Mrs. Craybill came with him on\na number of occasions, but there\nwas nothing improper about the\nvisits.\nMrs. Harry Emmart testified she\nheard the defendant tell Harry\nEmmart on October 13, 1946: \u201cHe\nmay be your brother, Harry, but I\nam going to kill him; without him\nmy life does not mean anything.\u201d\nDoctor\u2019s Report Cited.\nDr. Wendell Muncie, a Baltimore\npsychiatrist, said he saw Mrs. Em\nmart March 31, 1947. She had been\nreferred to him by a Winchester\nphysician, he said.\nDr. Muncie said Mrs. Emmart ap\npeared strained and in a nervous\nstate. He said she obviously was\nin need of treatment. On cross ex\namination he testified he did not\nconsider sending her to a mental\nhospital and did not diagnose her\ncase.\nThree or four more defense wit\nnesses are expected to testify today.\nThe prosecution is expected to call\nseveral rebuttal witnesses, includ\ning the superintendents of three\nVirginia mental institutions who\nsaw Mrs. Emmart during a four\nmonth period during which she was\nunder examination to determine\nher sanity.\nMcDaniel Larceny Trial\nDelayed in Arlington\nGrand larceny charges against\nBilly L. McDaniel, 32, former busi\nness associate of William Denekas\nWho was killed last month by a\nbomb explosion in his automobile,\nwere continued until August 17 in\nArlington Court today.\nMcDaniel requested the continu\nance and said he wanted to get an\nattorney. He is held in jail in lieu\nof $5,000 bond.\nMcDaniel is accused of taking\nequipment from the Old Dominion\nNeon Sign Co. in Which he and Mr.\nDenekas were partners. At the\ntime the property was stolen, it was\nunder a sheriff\u2019s levy, s\nMr. Denekas, 32, died shortly\nafter a bomb exploded as he started\nhis car in front of the Arlington\nhouse where he roomed. Police, who\nstill are seeking his slayer, ques\ntioned McDaniel among others fol\nlowing the slaying. McDaniel later\nwas released.\nSilver Spring Merchants Offer\nTo Sell Many Items Below Cost\nAn organization of 92 Silver\nSpring merchants today declared\nthere is a \"buyers\u2019 strike\u201d on\nagainst high prices\u2014and offered to\nlose $750,000 in an attempt to prove\nThe group, sponsors of thf second\nannual Shop Silver Spring Week\nwhich begins Saturday and contin\nues through August 7, said they\nwould sell \u201cmany items\u201d at prices\nbelow cost in an effort to show the\nwar-time prosperity is not begin\nning to decline.\n\"We do not feel a business slump\nis in prospect.\u201d said Charles H.\nKopeland, executive secretary of the\nt\nSilver spring uoara oi mue.\n\"Given the right prices, the Ameri\ncan public still will buy.\u2019\u2019\nMr. Kopeland said that after last\nyear\u2019s \u201cbargain week\u201d the mer\nchants reported retail gross sales of\nnearly *600,00 more than the best\nChristmas week in Silver Spring\nhistory.\nThe trade board official said a\ncommittee had been appointed to\ncheck newspaper advertisements of\nparticipating merchants to make\nsure articles displayed were being\noffered below cost. He said the\nmoney the merchants estimated\nthey would lose has already been\nwritten off as a loss on their books.\ni\nCommunity Adds 'Beach'\nTo Homemade Playground\n\u201cCome on, Mom!\u201d\nThe little girl ran ahead to join\nher neighbors, all clad in bathing\nsuits, under the hose spray at\n\"Monroe Beach.\u201d\nIt isn\u2019t really a beach. It\u2019s the\ncommunity back yard of the Na\ntional Capital Housing Authority\u2019s\nMonroe street development.\nBut residents of the housing proj\nect are resourceful. Instead of\ndreaming about the seashore, a\ngroup of mothers and their young\nsters were cooling off under a hose\nshower, soaking up sunshine, or\nlolling under an awning made of\ncanvas stretched over four pipe\nlengths yesterday afternoon.\nThe \u201cbeach\u201d is just one of the\nmany activities carried on by the\nMonroe dwellers through the Mon\nroe Community Council, an organi\nzation they formed to provide rec\nreation for their 300 children.\nFor AU the Family.\nAs Mrs. Glenn Scillian, 609 Law\nrence street N.E., mother of two\nchildren and secretary of the coun\ncil, explained it:\n\u201cWe aren\u2019t close to any play\nground, and there are only two\nblocks here with all these houses.\nThere was nothing much for the\nchildren to do.\u201d\nThe council, however, has given,\nnot only the children plenty to do,\nbut their mothers and fathers as\nwell. Fathers, in fact, have become\nthe backbone of the community\nactivities, carpentering facilities\nand directing sports.\nRobert F. Young, 607 Monroe\nstreet N.E., an attorney, is chair\nman of the council, which held its\norganizational meeting last May 14.\nAs yet, it has no meeting place,\nbut the members plan to get to\ngether about once a month.\nAfter the first meeting, Mrs.\nScillian, Mrs. Earl Heft, 3322\nSeventh street N.E., and a former\nMonroe resident, Mrs. Robert\nStiehler, who since has moved to\nnearby Maryland, canvassed each\nhouse in the project to find out\nwhat activities were favored and\nhow much each of the 91 families\nwould be willing to take part.\nBall Field Made Available.\nThe older boys, whose ball playing\nused to be restricted by the tots\nwho got in their way. now play\non a field made available to them\nby nearby St. Paul s College, under\nthe direction of Richard S. Law\nrenson, 3302 Seventh street N.E.,\nand William Schneckenburger, 609\nMonroe street N.E.\nMr. Lawrenson works for Govern\nment Services, Inc., and is the fa\nther of three children. Mr. Scheck\nenberger, who has one child, works\nfor the Capital Transit Co.\nA favorite activity for boys under\n12 is the hiking club, organized by\nJ. N. Lopes, 3332 Seventh street\nN.E.\nMrs. Scillian is chairman of the\nCrafts Subcommittee. Several of\nthe mothers help in this activity,\nshowing children how to make pup\npets for the community puppet\nshow, flags of the United Nations,\nwoven novelties and plaster of paris\nfigurines.\nMrs. Loretta H. Hennessey, a\nschool teacher, of 631 Monroe street\nN.E., instructs children in square\ndancing. Now taking graduate work\nat George Washington University,\nMrs. Hennessey found material right\nat home for her term paper in a\ncourse on the use of community\nresources.\nStar Movies Shown.\nThe Recreation Department helps\nout the council, including the pres\nentation of free movies sponsored\nby The Star every other Friday\nnight. Business concerns near the\nproject have helped by supplying\nequipment and a soft drink machine.\nHusbands and wives work to\ngether in council activities. One\nexample is James W. Whitall, 3324\nSeventh street N.E., who is vice\nchairman, and Mrs. Whitall, who is\nchairman of Ways and Means Com\nmittee. They have two children.\nMrs. Young, wife of the chairman,\nhas a library in her home for the\nuse of the children.\nThe fathers are the mainstay of\nthe Building and Construction,\nCommittee, which provides tables,\nbulletin boards and other equip\nment. The committee is headed by\nMaurice A. Madsen, 3318 Seventh\nstreet N.E., who also is treasurer of\nthe council.\nAs to why the Monroe residents\nfeels they have succeeded in an all\nround community recreation plan\nwhere others have failed, Mrs.\nScillian declared: \u201cThere's just an\nunusually nice group of people here.\u201d\nToday Is the Deadline\nFor Absentee Ballots\nIn Virginia Primaries\nToday is the deadline for\nsubmitting applications for\nabsentee ballots for Tuesday\u2019s\nVirginia primaries.\nThe applications, containing\n23 cents in stamps or coin, must\nbe in the hands of precinct\nregistrars today so that bal\nlots can be returned to voters\nby registered mail.\nVoters must fill out their bal\nlots in the presence of a no\ntary public, have the ballot no\ntarized and return them to the\nsecretary of the cbunty or city\nelectoral board either by reg\nistered mail or in person on\nor before the day of the pri\nmaries.\nSilver Spring Post Is Sold\nTo Editor Blair Lee III\nPurchase of the Silver Spring\nPost for an undisclosed sum was\nannounced today by Blair Lee III,\neditor and publisher of the Mary\nland News, a Montgomery County\nweekly.\nMr. Lee said he also agreed to\nlease the Post\u2019s printing plant at\n933 Selim road, Silver Spring. The\nplant will be operated by Anchor\nPress, Inc., of which Mr. Lee is\nvice president and treasurer, and\nwill be used exclusively for com\nmercial printing.\nThe Post has been operated by\nGlen E. Mahar and has been in\nexistence for about nine years. Its\nsale removes the only weekly com\npetitor of the Maryland News in\nSilver Spring.\nAlexandria Man Hurt\nWhen Hit by Robber\nJohn O. Ledbetter, 41, of Route 4,\nAlexandria, was admitted to Alex\nandria Hospital last night with\nhead injuries suffered, he said, about\n20 hours earlier when he was robbed\nnear the Mount Vernon High School\nin Fairfax County.\nFairfax police said Mr. Ledbetter\nreported he got off a bus and started\nwalking to his brother\u2019s home when\na car pulled up, a man got out and\nstruck him over the head. After\nhitting him, the man robbed him of\nfrom between $15 and $20, police\nwere told.\nMr. Ledbetter\u2019s condition was de\nscribed as \u201cgood\u201d at the hospital\ntoday.\n4\nRockville Mayor Calls\nSewer Line Extension\nDenial 'Short Sighted'\nMayor G. La Mar Kelly of Rock\nville today described as \u201cstupid and\npolitically short sighted\u201d the recent\ndenial by the Montgomery County\nCommissioner of requests to ex\ntend sewer lines to three areas\nadjacent to Rockville.\nIn rejecting the petitions, the\ncommissioner said special legisla\ntion was needed at the 1949 session\nof the General Assembly.\nMayor Kelly maintained today,\nhowever, that the county heads have\nauthority to issue up to $500,000 in\nbonds to finance the project.\nnuiiwuiMnan icwpuuu,\nDeclaring he was speaking from\na \u201chumanitarian\u201d point of view, Mr.\nKelly accused the commissioners of\n\"following poor leadership and ad\nvice in denying the approximately\n1,000 residents of Lincoln Park.\nCroyden and Harriet Park \\he right\nto decent sanitation by having\nsewers installed.\u201d Lincoln Park is\na colored settlement.\nHe said Rockville cannot extend\nits own sewer line because the three\ncommunities are outside the city\nlimits. But he added that the town\nstands ready to process sewage from\nthe area In its sewage disposal plant\nif the county installs the necessary\nSewer lines and advances sufficient\nfunds to Rockville to expand its\nfacilities. The money would be re\nturned to the county from assess\nments on abutting property.\nPoints to Health Hazard.\nMore than a year ago, Mayor\nKelly recalled, Dr. V. L. Ellicott,\ncounty health officer, cited the\nhealth hazards resulting from lack\nof sewage facilities. As a result,\nhe said, the city and county co\noperated in sponsoring an engineer\ning study which, he claimed, shows\nthat sewers could be installed.\nAt present, according to Mr. Kelly,\nmost of those living in the three\nadjacent communities get water\nfrom a privately owned system con\nsisting of two wells.\nIndians to Be Taught\nIn English for 5 Years\nVice chancellors of India\u2019s 24 uni\nversities, meeting in New Delhi, de\ncided that English is to remain the\nmedium of instruction for five years.\nAfter that, it must be replaced by\nregional languages, but English will\nremain a compulsory subject in ail\nIndian schools.\nk\nSurplus Rises\nTo $20,473,515\nIn Maryland\nRevenues for Year\nWere $9,240,610\nAbove Estimates\nBy th# Associated frost\nBALTIMORE, July 29.\u2014Hie sur\nplus In the Maryland general fund\nstood atf *20,473515 on June 30\u2014last\nday of the fiscal year\u2014the con\u00ab\ntrailer's office reported today.\nTotal general fund receipts for th*\nyear were $58,866,362.\nThat was *9,960,677 more than th*\n*10,512,837 the office had estimated\nwould be on hand when the budget\nfor the year was drawn up.\nRevenues were *9,240,610 more\nthan anticipated, and reversions\nfrom department which did not use\nup all the monies allowed them\namounted to $2,241,859.\nThis would have meant an $11,482,\n469 increase in the general fund.\nBut two special session of the legis\nlature authorized general fund ap\npropriations totalling $1,521,792 for\nthe fiscal year.\nStatement issued.\nThe controller\u2019s office issued this\nstatement ot general fund net re\nceipts collected for the fiscal year:\nFranchise tax on gross re\nceipts _ $3,324,432\nTax on insurance premiums 3,453,200\nIncome tax. 14,751,381\nRetail sales tax- 23,302,540\nCollateral and direct in\nheritance 1,212.920\nMaryland estate tax- 565,154\nAll other... 12,256,723\nTotal .$58,866,362\nMeanwhile, the State Roads Com\nmission reported it received nearly\n$2,000,000 more in tax receipts allo\ncated for road construction than\nestimated in this year\u2019s budget.\nTotal Receipts Listed.\nCarl L. Wannen, controller of the\ncommission, said yesterday that\ntotal receipts from the 5-cent gaso\nline tax and the motor vehicle\nrevenue fund for the year ended\nJune 30 were $31,649,640.\nOf this amount, $13,851,093 was\nearmarked for State road construc\ntion, $4,193,568 goes for road main*\ntenance, Baltimore City gets $8,162,\n986, and counties and other subdivi\nsions get $5,441,991.\nThe gasoline tax accounted for\n$18,822,818 and the motor vehicle\nrevenue fund for $12,826,822. Of\nthe latter, $4,439,684 represents re\nceipts from the 2 per cent exlse tax\non all automobiles titled in Mary\nland.\nReceipts from the excise tax were\nnearly $1,350,000 more than the\n$3,090,000 that had been estimated\nfrom this source in the budget.\nOne-half of the gasoline tax re\nceipts are automatically earmarked\nfor road construction. The $9,411,\n409 for road work from this source\ncompares with the original esti\nmate of $8,843,907.\nThe original estimate of gaso\nline tax and motor vehicles receipts\nfor counties and municipalities had\nbeen $5,201,000. _\nLeague in Arlington\nTo Hear Candidates\nThe Arlington Better Government\nLeague last night called a meeting\nfor August 25 to hear \u201cindependent\"\ncandidates for the County Board\nvacancy, with a view of indorsing\none of them.\nTo date, only one independent\ncandidate has entered the November\nelection race. He Is I. Lee Potter,\nbuilder and musician.\nThe league decided to issue ques\ntionnaires to any Independents who\nmay file and urged that answers be\nreturned not later than August 15.\nThe group adopted a resolution\nfavoring the passage by Congress of\nthe anti-poll tax bill. Louis Knight,\nMrs. Joseph Accardo and Malcolm\nMiller, president, said they did not\nbelieve Virginia voters will adopt\nthe pending State constitutional\namendment abolishing the tax. They\ncriticized the postponement of the\npoll tax referendum from 1948 to\n1949 and also the plan of substituting\nannual registration.\nHarley M. Williams, a former\npresident, attacked the Arlington\nDemocratic Executive Committee\n\"sponsorship\u201d of the three candi\ndates in the primary to be held\nTuesday. These candidates are Alfred\nIE. Frisbie, the Incumbent; Harold\nSchilz and William Nemeth.\nFairfax Woman Wins\nDamage Suit Appeal\nBy tH\u00ab Associated Pros*\nRICHMOND, Va.. July 29\u2014The\nVirginia Supreme Court of Appeals\nyesterday granted a writ of error to\nMrs. Betty Jane Via from a Judg\nment of the Circuit Court of Fair\nfax County directing a verdict\nagainst her in an automobile in\njury suit.\nMrs. Via was injured seriously In\nan accident on the Mount Vernon\nMemorial highway February 9, 1947,\nwhen she was a passenger with her\nhusband in an automobile owned by\nFrank Parker and operated by Vic\ntor Parker. The car and a truck\ncollided.\nThe Trial Court held that evi\ndence submitted by Mrs. Via failed\nto sustain gross negligence on the\npart of Victor Parker and also failed\nto show recoverable negligence on\nthe part of the truck driver.\nTrade Promotion Unit Meets\nAn organization meeting of the\nCommittee of Western Montgomery\nCounty for the Promotion of Local\nBusiness was held last night at Nor\nmandy Farms, which is owned by\nthe committee president, Mrs. Mar\nJory Hendricks.\nPlace Sunday Classified\nAds Early!\nClassified ad customers de\nsiring to place ads in The\nSunday Star are urged to call\nthem in early in the week.\nThis will eliminate the last\nminute rush to place ads and\nwill assure eveigr one prompt\nand efficient service. Tour\nco-operation will be appre\nciated.\nRemember The Star\u2019s new\ntelephone number is Sterttnr\nMM.\nk","height":"31316","width":"22228"}}
